{"cursor":"32588","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox film\n| name = Ran image = Kuroran.jpg caption = Japanese release poster director =\n| Akira Kurosawa producer = Katsumi Furukawa Serge Silberman Masato\n| Hara Hisao Kurosawa writer = Akira Kurosawa Hideo Oguni Masato Ide\n| starring = Tatsuya Nakadai Akira Terao Jinpachi Nezu Daisuke\n| Ryu Mieko Harada Yoshiko Miyazaki Peter music = Toru Takemitsu\n| cinematography = Asakazu Nakai Takao SaitÅ Masaharu Ueda editing = Akira\n| Kurosawa studio = Greenwich Film Productions Herald Ace Nippon Herald\n| Films distributor = Toho Orion Classics released =  runtime = 160 minutes\n| country = Japan France language = Japanese budget = US$12,000,000 gross =\n}} is a 1985 Japanese-French jidaigeki epic film directed and co-written by\nAkira Kurosawa. The film stars Tatsuya Nakadai as Hidetora Ichimonji, an aging\n[[Sengoku period|Sengoku]]-era warlord who decides to abdicate as ruler in favor\nof his three sons. The story is based on legends of the daimyo MÅri Motonari, as\nwell as on the Shakespearean tragedy [[King Lear]].\n\nRan was Kurosawa's last epic. With a budget of $12 million, it was the most\nexpensive Japanese film ever produced up to that time. Ran was released on May 31, 1985 at the Tokyo International Film Festival and on\nJune 1, 1985 in Japan. The film was hailed for its powerful images and use of\ncolorâcostume designer Emi Wada won an Academy Award for Costume Design for her\nwork on Ran. The distinctive Gustav Mahler-inspired film score, written by Toru\nTakemitsu, plays in isolation with ambient sound muted.\n","linknr":617,"url":"Ran_(film)","recorded":1374858058,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ran_(film)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ran_(film)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wi